>>114695401
There were other amps before Mesa - HiWatt became popular when Townsend switched to them in the late 60's. (Townsend didn't use Marshalls that long, and I can't recall seeing any recordings made with them.) Gilmour, Townsend, Tull, and a bunch of other bands recorded and toured with HiWatt amps.
Boogies came out in the early 70's, made popular by guys like Santana, but they were boutique combo amps, the stacks didn't come until much later - the IIC+ came out in the early 80's, and Hammett made them sought after when he started using them on Metallica albums. Boogies were handmade in the 70s, basically, and expensive. And they weren't nearly as loud as a stack. Mesa's became more affordable (relatively) when they moved in 1980 and built a factory.
In the 70's, you had Marshall, Fender, HiWatt, and Vox as the sought after, "I made it" amps, and you had tons of other choices, like Laney, Ampeg, Music Man, Randall. and early Peavy. Nuget put Fender Deluxe's on the map using them live and in the studio, Queen made Vox continue being huge, and Skynyrd put Peavey on the map.
You're right about plexi's being around forever, until they were replaced by the JCMs, but Marshalls were taken on the road because they could take being bounced around in the back of a truck - and they were LOUD. PAs kinda sucked in the 70's, so the louder you were, the better. Jimmy Page used Marshalls on the road, but in the studio he used everything - Vox, Fender, Hiwatt, all of them.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114696610
The thing about Hiwatts thought is not only they were loud, they were CLEAN. People used them love because they had high clean headroom at deafeningly high volumes. Marshall’s break up at a lower volume, which makes them great for that overdriven sound in areas. Also, to add what makes them special compared to other overdriven amps is not only the volume, but the mid-range. They have a sharp presence and a punchy yet tight low-end which cuts through over the bass and drums in a way a Fender amp simply cannot (they have a lot of flubby bass and a mid-low peak instead of a mid-high peak like Marshalls).

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114694873
For overdriven rock, theyre kind of hard to beat. They have a huge sound with a tight bottom end and theyre voiced pretty bright with a real emphasis on the midrange, Reallly easy to cut through the mix.

Vox is kinda like that but the bottom end is looser and the emphasis is on the UPPER midrange with a more pronounced top end. It's a great sound, but not quite as "in your face" as a Marshall.

Fender is a different thing altogether. It's a "rounder" with the mids scooped. Plenty of bass and treble, huge cleans, really "creamy" overdrive.

The point is, as cliched as they may be, Marshall has a very distinct, big rock sound. Coupled with a lot of influential players using them, they keep finding their way into music.

>>114694873
Aside from everything that can be lumped into emotional associations and marketing, Marshalls have a sound that is very easy to distinguish, especially when they're pushed to distortion volume. I describe the tone as being very mid-forward, sometimes to the point of being unpleasant and box-y, but it's that same EQ profile which makes it so useful. If you're on stage with a loud hard rock band, it's easy for guitars to lose their clarity inside the other instruments. With Marshall, those guitar frequencies which are richest in musical information are the ones that get pushed the hardest. Anyone that has ever seen a band with two guitarists where one uses a marshall half stack while the other uses literally any other stack will know what I mean. In my opinion, Marshall sound isn't as "pretty" in isolation compared to other brands but it really does let a band more effectively communicate to a crowd.

>>114695240

For 99% of amps, variation in tubes account for absolutely no influence tone. I give 1% allowance for the maniacs who make boutique amps and actually experiment with novel ways of getting sound.

And I'm just throwing this in because (unsurprisingly) no one else has mentioned it, but when we're talking about high gain tones, your sound profile is going to be mostly in the hands of the speakers you're plugging into. An orange head plugged into a marshall cab is going to strongly give that marshall tone more than anything. The orange head is only going to slightly color the tone. For some people it's not obvious that transducers at the output end of the signal chain would account for the most influential filter of tone (for high gain at least).

The band was in the dark the whole time. After many meetings between Hayley, her manager and the labels they decided to sign her to Atlantic records. We didn’t understand why Hayley was the only one signing the contract since we were told this was a “band”, but we were too young to grasp all of this. So far, Zac and I haven’t signed with another label, although I guess our part of Paramore sure could. Next thing we knew we were having a signing party for Hayley.
>
>Our next move was to rerecord her solo demos with our own music rather than studio musicians to make it sound more genuine. Meanwhile, we tossed around band names. I wrote out a list of names, including “Paramore”, a name my old band with Taylor and Jason Clark had thought about using. Obviously, we settled on that name. The label received the rerecorded demos and once again tried to fire the entire band, saying we were terrible. Thankfully Hayley and I had been writing some new songs together (Hallelujah, Here We Go Again) that the label was pleased with so that acted as leverage for the band to stay. The label and management then decided to build our band up the grass-roots route. They put Hayley on Fueled by Ramen not making it known she was signed to Atlantic as well. All the while we still questioned whether or not we were an actual band, but Hayley continued to insist we were, despite our being ignored and pushed around by the label.

The problem with metal is its lack of a musical vocabulary, and the dissonant "xyz" has become the premier buzzword in the community in which every band is seen as "DsO/Gorguts" worship, but don't have that much similarities in how they employ dissonance and use it as a musical device.

To quote a guy from last.fm:
>I don't understand why everyone feels the need to compare every "dissonant" metal band to Deathspell Omega these days. It does such a disservice to bands like Skáphe who have genuinely created their own sound signature and just unfortunately makes it seem like no one is really paying any real mind or attention when listening to them. DsO's dissonance is defined by a very heavy reliance on minor 9ths and non-functional harmony, almost none of which I hear in this band. You would never hear someone say Chopin sounds just like Brahms or Schumann because they all sound "harmonious" yet in metal circles these surface-level comparisons are the norm. The "mass influence/inspiration" argument makes no sense either; there are a million musicians who claim to be influenced by Miles Davis or Mozart yet still sound nothing like them.

>>114687616
Same shit, 2100 projects in almost every genre.
Start sorting them, at least - by personal sentiment, genre, time signature, etc. As many of my categories overlapped, I sorted and duplicated their shortcuts into folders, as opposed to the files themselves. But understandably, I got lazy and stopped doing it a while ago.

A better way is to write and append way more descriptive filenames as you work on the project - though this breaks any shortcuts to the file (but shortcuts might have been a dumb idea anyway).

That's why I wish there was an easy way to add tags to each file in Windows explorer, as opposed to writing tags onto huge filenames - then to search/sort by those tags. Even better would be for FL to embed a little audio preview of the project in each file, so I could quickly find melodies I'm looking for.

But the problem of finding a concept to unify them wasn't so much creative or intellectual for me, but finding the feeling and emotion to actually give a shit about all these vacuous (but very intricate and catchy) tunes, and dig for any human emotion they actually stir in me - then figuring out how to strengthen and dissect it through every available sonic palette. And to do that point where it might actually stir that same emotion in someone else.

Cause the main thing that drives it is personal expression, and expression cannot exist in a vacuum - it has to help me relate to some actual IRL peer groups or romantic interests. The moment those disappear is the moment music becomes technical wankery and an escapist dopamine outlet for me.

Also: modesty, taste, and scale. I really want to make my epic-dark-ambient-metal-shoegaze-symphonic-ethno-pagan opera, but each extra flavour only makes it harder to blend into something non-absurd - not that it's not possible with enough technical skill and vision, but know and explore your limits.

So I'd start with small concepts and make them as effective as possible - nail the atmosphere, etc.

You need music theory to even be able to enjoy Petzold. It's a lot like Harry Potter, if you learn enough "writing theory" you discover Harry Potter is the best in history.

I started to learn music composition and music theory the last months because I need music for my personal projects. Basic things like counting to three, or being able to understand the structure of something, a minuet for example. It's pretty cool to start to count the rhythm and realize the entire piece is like a /s4s/ thread, where there's superior shitposts that are clearly invisible or impossible to view, meta shitposts that are metaphysical in some sense; they're invisible structures, the epic meme of the piece. And how that meta structure repeats from the entire piece where a single measure of this giant invisible shitpost is about 5 minutes.

Another cool thing is when you start to view music as a piece of shitposting, seeing how chords are memes, and the type of meme is its topic, and start to visualize a piece of instrumental music like a copypasta, and you see clearly how the melody acts like the posts in a /s4s/ thread. And the key modulations are like rolling dubs.

It's not that difficult. See pic related. Put attention to how he repeats frogs, like the green frogs, which he then start to repeat into bigger frogs (the green frogs), which he uses to build even bigger frogs.

When you see Petzold's music and start counting, start to be aware of his use of shitposting, of how he keeps layering meme on top of meme, it's an amazing experience.

Music theory might seem boring as shit but it's really helpful. Chords and the major scale are good to start with.

posts.name: microdoser_of_toxic_ex_gfs
posts.com:
get the Beatles book. learn the songs. they will teach you how to use chords in inventive ways on an intuitive level and you'll have vocal melodies to show you how to write to them in interesting ways, as well. its important to get inspired, so find amazing music you like.

Elliott Smith is also an amazing chord progression writer/melody writer. Lemme hit you with some excellent chord songs.

Listen closely to the intros. One of my biggest tips is to listening to parts and songs on repeat constantly, if you want to internalize an intelligent intuition informed by the best musicians and writers. Listen closely to these intros. You need to learn to write that good if you want to contribute to the musical canon of the world. We need it. You as a beginner are an important light of hope. Get the fuck in there.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wYqZiK6gGo8
"Coming Up Roses" - Elliott Smith

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=t1Jm5epJr10
"I Am The Walrus"

Key changes are ESSENTIAL to keep things interesting and inventive for yourself and for the world. These two songs are incredible for profession and key change info. The world DOES NOT need any more mediocre instrumentalists. Get guitar-godly with it. You have the 10 fingers like anyone else, and the lobes of brain and resources to enhance every bit of your playing and knowledge. Do it.

There’s nothing unique or important about your background. Practice like everyone else and you will get good

There is no excuse to not have a guitar in your hands practicing SOMETHING at all times while you’re watching tv, a movie, YouTube or listening to a podcast, whether it’s just chord changes or soloing licks

Metronomes really help when trying to learn to play fast techniques, but tapping your foot works too, though not as reliable.

The best way to learn to play smooth and fast like doing fast lead guitar solos is to practice at the speed where you can play the lick PERFECTLY, WHILE FULLY RELAXED, AND WITHOUT THINKING ABOUT IT. This is the fastest way to develop speed; by practicing slow. If you try to force speed by practicing faster than you can play, it will take forever and your technique will be very shitty

Also anyone who tells you “hurrr durrr you can’t practice while watching TV, you need to give it your full undivided attention” is a fucking idiot who sucks shit at guitar. Every metal shredder in the fucking WORLD got good by noodling on the couch while watching Friends re-runs. If you actually believe that anyone has the mental stamina or attention span required to put in the thousands of hours needed to get to Eddie Van Halen level, just by sitting and staring at the wall in agonising boredom, then you are a retard

Source: I’m the type of guy who the staff are *actually* impressed by when he plays guitar at a music store. Yes I can brag about this, because I earned it

Anyway have fun and best of luck on your guitar journey

Don't be afraid to step out of your comfort zone to try learn something above your skill level. Also don't afraid to give up on said hard song/riff/lead and return to it later as you don't want to make yourself hate the instrument. When learning things, take it slow. Repeat things at 40, 50, 60 ,70 percent speed until you get comfy with it. >>114685813
The earliest math rock bands were noise rock bands experimenting with time signatures and other rhythmic dynamics, like slint, bitch magnet, breadwinner, and bastro. '89 or '90 was the year when a lot of these artists developed their sounds. These groups inspired other indie and alternative groups which had incredibly varied sounds, from the erratic like polvo ( see "thermal treasure") to the more structured pop songwriting like jawbox (see their song "68") or poster children (see "dynamite chair"). The twinkle guitar style guitar emerged with bands like Don cab, Cap'n jazz, or more mellower groups like seam (ex bitch magnet frontman) over the course of the decade until it became almost the default guitar style by the beginning of the century (see hella, minus the bear, toe, American football, etc.) at which point the earlier math rock groups were almost forgotten.
By the 2010s every scene kid who learned guitar to impress chicks at hot topic traded in their gages for flannel and made "twinkly Midwest emo math rock"
That's where we're at more than a decade later
But essentially math rock can really be used to describe any alternative/indie/noise/post-hardcore punk rock group that utilizes dynamic rhythms. It's just a way of categorizing bands according to rhythm the same way "jangle pop" is a way of categorizing bands who use acoustic and bright clean electric guitars with arpeggiating chords

>>114698913
Honestly as a French speaker, I kinda like the Anglophone/Germanic system of moveable do.

Here, "Do" refers to the note called C in English and nothing else, "ré" is D, "mi" is E, etc. You can't just call any note "do" just because it's the first scale degree.

I remember finding it kind of stupid how Anglophones did it when I first learned about it (not to mention, calling it "solfège" - in French that just means musical notation and theory in general) but honestly, we kinda do that already anyways - if I'm learning a melody by ear without knowing the pitch, I'll typically pretend it's in C to make my life easier.

Plus it's nice having different names for actual pitches and scale degrees.

"Ti" is an absolutely ridiculous name though.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
Nothing expensive, but I have lots of late 80s and early 90s rack guitar stuff. Pic related is my favorite rack unit/valve dsp preamp and I am emotionally very attached to it because lots of memories with recordings and old bands.

All my stuff works still in perfect condition for some reason even though all of them have original electronics inside, but they must be running 30-35 years old at this point and I kinda realize that recapping and failure is inevitable at some point. I've only done some minor things to them like changed lithium battery or a small 12AX7 tube and kept them out of heat/cold, moisture and dust in sealed rack.

I'm starting to learn diy electronics because in 5-15 years I'm pretty sure they will all fail and perhaps, if not repair them myself totally, can identify the problems myself, order parts and perhaps visit local electronic shops and repairers and make them do it for me to get them back in working condition. Probably would be wiser to ditch them all and buy new stuff, but as I said, I am emotionally very attached to these units.
